│                                                                                                                              │
│ **1. Analyze the crash**                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The crash occurs in `opt` when running the `loop-vectorize` pass on a specific LLVM IR file.                                 │
│ The assertion failure is: `Assertion 'State.TypeAnalysis.inferScalarType(RepRecipe) == Cloned->getType() && "inferred type   │
│ and type from generated instructions do not match"' failed.`                                                                 │
│ This happens inside `scalarizeInstruction` in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp`.                              │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The backtrace shows the crash happens during the execution of a `VPReplicateRecipe`, which is part of the VPlan execution    │
│ framework used by the loop vectorizer. `VPReplicateRecipe` is used to generate scalar code for each lane of a vector         │
│ operation. The assertion indicates a type mismatch between the type inferred by `VPlan's TypeAnalysis` and the type of the   │
│ actual cloned instruction generated during scalarization.                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ **2. Examine the IR and the code**                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The problematic IR involves a `select` instruction whose result is truncated:                                                │
│ ```llvm                                                                                                                      │
│   %sel = select i1 %cmp, i32 0, i32 %and                                                                                     │
│   %sel.trunc = trunc i32 %sel to i16                                                                                         │
│ ```                                                                                                                          │
│ The `select` instruction `%sel` has type `i32`, and it is immediately used by a `trunc` to `i16`.                            │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The failing assertion is in `scalarizeInstruction`. This function clones an instruction to generate the per-lane scalar      │
│ version. The assertion compares the type inferred by `VPTypeAnalysis::inferScalarType` with the type of the cloned           │
│ instruction.                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ Let's look at `VPTypeAnalysis::inferScalarType` in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlan.cpp`. This function tries to         │
│ determine the scalar type of a `VPValue`. For a `VPReplicateRecipe`, it has special logic:                                   │
│ ```cpp                                                                                                                       │
│ // In VPTypeAnalysis::inferScalarType(const VPReplicateRecipe *Recipe)                                                       │
│ ...                                                                                                                          │
│   // If the recipe has a single user that is a trunc, the recipe is vectorized                                               │
│   // in the trunc's type.                                                                                                    │
│   if (Recipe->hasOneUse())                                                                                                   │
│     if (auto *Trunc = dyn_cast<TruncInst>(Recipe->getUnderlyingInstr()->user_back()))                                        │
│       return Trunc->getDestTy();                                                                                             │
│ ...                                                                                                                          │
│ ```                                                                                                                          │
│ This logic seems to be the cause of the problem. If the `select` instruction (`%sel`) is represented by a                    │
│ `VPReplicateRecipe`, and its only user is the `trunc` instruction (`%sel.trunc`), `inferScalarType` will return the          │
│ destination type of the `trunc`, which is `i16`.                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ However, when `scalarizeInstruction` clones the original `select` instruction, the cloned instruction will have the type of  │
│ the original `select`, which is `i32`. The assertion then fails because the inferred type (`i16`) does not match the cloned  │
│ instruction's type (`i32`).                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ **3. Formulate a fix**                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The logic in `inferScalarType` is too aggressive. It assumes that if the single user is a `trunc`, the replicated            │
│ instruction itself can be generated with the truncated type. This might be true in some vectorization scenarios, but it's    │
│ incorrect for the general case of scalarization performed by `scalarizeInstruction`, which simply clones the original        │
│ instruction.                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The fix is to remove this special-case logic for `trunc` from `VPTypeAnalysis::inferScalarType`. The scalar type of a        │
│ `VPReplicateRecipe` should be the type of its underlying instruction, which is what the general logic will fall back to.     │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ I will use `sed` to comment out the problematic `if` block in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlan.cpp`.                     │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The relevant lines are around 200 in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlan.cpp`.                                              │
│ ```cpp                                                                                                                       │
│ // If the recipe has a single user that is a trunc, the recipe is vectorized                                                 │
│ // in the trunc's type.                                                                                                      │
│ if (Recipe->hasOneUse())                                                                                                     │
│   if (auto *Trunc = dyn_cast<TruncInst>(Recipe->getUnderlyingInstr()->user_back()))                                          │
│     return Trunc->getDestTy();                                                                                               │
│ ```                                                                                                                          │
│ I will comment out these four lines.                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                      │
│ sed -i -e '200,203s/^/\/\/ /' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlan.cpp                                                        │
│ ```                                                                                                                          │
